question_text: The words “feat,” “humanly impossible,” and “impenetrable barrier” in paragraph 1 affect the tone of the paragraph because they
options: highlight the idea that only the most skilled runners would be able to run a four-minute mile.
emphasize the idea that running a mile in less than four minutes was a seemingly unattainable goal.
convey the competitiveness among elite runners to consistently set and break speed records.
show the intensity of the training programs athletes endure in order to achieve their goals.

question_text: How did interval training affect Bannister’s performance?
options: It helped him learn how to moderate his pace while running.
It helped him understand the importance of running with a team.
It helped him improve his pace and stamina while running.
It helped him decrease his recovery time after an intense run.

question_text: Which sentence best supports the idea that Bannister needed an alternative to “logical planning” in order to accomplish his goal?
options: “Bannister’s performance was a disappointment for him and his country, Great Britain.” (paragraph 2)
“The amateur athlete decided to use intensive interval training to develop endurance and speed.” (paragraph 3)
“For these workouts, Bannister ran an interval of ten consecutive laps on a quarter-mile track, aiming for sixty seconds each lap.” (paragraph 3)
“Frustrated by the plateau he had reached, Bannister took a break from training and went mountain climbing for three days.” (paragraph 4)

question_text: Which sentence from the passage indicates that Bannister nearly made a mistake that would have cost him the world record?
options: “By early 1954, Bannister had succeeded in lowering his quarter-mile pace to sixty-one seconds, but he had to shave off at least one more second in order to reach his target.” (paragraph 4)
“When the starting pistol fired, Brasher pounced into the lead, and Bannister followed behind his first rabbit.” (paragraph 6)
“Propelled by the excitement, Bannister lost his instinctive feel for his pace and shouted ‘Faster!’ at Brasher.” (paragraph 7)
“At the beginning of the back straightaway of the track, Bannister bolted past Chataway.” (paragraph 7)

question_text: The phrase “a new mindset had taken root” in paragraph 8 conveys the idea that
options: runners recognized that running a mile in under four minutes was physically possible.
breaking the four-minute-mile barrier was no longer considered an impressive feat for elite runners.
runners understood how hard they would have to train in order to run a mile in under four minutes.
entering races in an attempt to break the four-minute-mile barrier became commonplace for elite runners.

question_text: Bannister’s loss in the 1952 Olympics influenced his decision to pursue breaking the four-minutemile barrier by
options: allowing him to recognize his weaknesses and improve his running ability
prompting him to take a different approach to his regular training.
motivating him to prove to himself that he could set and achieve a goal.
giving him the opportunity to reach a goal no runner had ever accomplished.

question_text: How does the author’s use of chronological structure contribute to the development of ideas in the passage?
options: It presents the increasing physical effects of Bannister’s intense training methods as he prepared to break the four-minute-mile barrier.
It shows the increase in Bannister’s confidence in his ability to break the four-minute mile barrier.
It emphasizes the key events in Bannister’s life that inspired him to break the four-minutemile barrier.
It highlights the progression of Bannister’s training and details about his successful attempt to break the four-minute-mile barrier.

question_text:
Read these sentences from paragraph 7.

Bannister said, “I felt that the moment of a lifetime had come. There was no pain, only a great unity of movement and aim.”

The sentences contribute to the development of ideas in the passage by showing that Bannister
options: knew that he was about to achieve the goal he had worked toward.
was no longer experiencing personal disappointment from his past failure in the Olympics.
felt grateful to his teammates for helping him take the lead.
was satisfied that his training had helped him perfect his running technique.

question_text: The fireworks in the poem represent the speaker’s
options: wish to return to a simpler way of living.
bittersweet feelings about leaving the past behind.
high expectations for everyday life.
reflections on past interactions with relatives.

question_text: The comparison in lines 8–9 of the poem is used to convey
options: the muffled pounding of explosions in the distance.
the way lightning streaks through the clouds
the echoes of thunder on an autumn night.
the glow of sparks falling from the sky.

question_text:
Read lines 22–23 from the poem.

the sky at night written upon
with those jewels.

What does the word choice in these lines convey about the speaker?
options: The speaker values material possessions.
The speaker imagines that the fireworks are magical.
The speaker believes that the country setting is distinctive.
The speaker cherishes the memory of seeing fireworks as a child.

question_text: The use of italics on the word “night” in line 24 is most likely intended to emphasize the
options: sense of mystery in the darkness.
sense of absolute darkness.
speaker’s fear of night.
speaker’s certainty about that night.

question_text: What is the purpose of the repeated words “rising and falling” in lines 26 and 37?
options: to create a distinction between solitude and meaningful interaction
to demonstrate a connection between the speaker’s past and present
to emphasize the speaker’s attention to the surrounding sounds
to compare the fireworks to common sights and sounds

question_text: What impact does the phrase “Everything is a constant celebration” (line 33) have in the poem?
options: It reveals that the speaker finds the city more pleasurable than the country.
It suggests that the persistent brightness of the city can be overwhelming to the speaker.
It implies that what is normal in the city was unusual in the country.
It emphasizes the hectic pace of daily life in the city

question_text:
Read lines 41–42 from the poem.

I kept waiting for those
childhood bursts, watching as they escorted us home.

How does this memory affect the speaker?
options: The speaker believes it is impossible to ever return to a place in the past.
The speaker is still amused by the impatience felt during fireworks displays.
The speaker now regrets abandoning the rural way of life
The speaker feels a sense of comfort when reflecting on the past.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 2.

But cuteness and weirdness aside, the platypus research results are a gold mine for medical researchers.

The sentence contributes to the overall structure of the excerpt by
options: shifting the focus of the excerpt from the platypus’s unique appearance to its physiology.
highlighting how the platypus’s unusual appearance has attracted scientists’ attention.
revealing current ideas about the genetic background of the platypus.
introducing the platypus’s scientific significance that the rest of the excerpt develops.

question_text: The phrase “evolutionary DNA tapestry” in paragraph 3 conveys the idea that the platypus
options: has a rich and diverse genetic history linked to reptiles, birds, and other mammals.
was able to develop its mammalian and reptilian traits at different points in time.
continues to be the best resource for studying the evolution of animal genomes.
is especially useful to researchers because its genes have never been altered.

question_text: How does paragraph 8 fit into the overall structure of the excerpt?
options: It provides a transition from the discussion of the platypus genome to a discussion on comparative genomics.
It introduces the way that scientists solved the problem of how to study complex human genomes through comparative genomics
It contrasts the efforts made to study the different parts of the human genome with the efforts made to study certain animal genomes.
It elaborates on the idea that deciphering genetic signals is a rigorous research challenge.

question_text: Which sentence gives the best summary of the section “Same and Different” (paragraphs 9–11)?
options: The platypus is the most recent of several species whose genomes have been compared with the human genome.
Comparative genomics is an effective way to examine a variety of different species, from single celled organisms to large mammals.
Comparing human genes with the genes of other animals and studying which genes are the same across species yield valuable information that may lead to a greater understanding of human disease.
Scientists are able to use computers in order to compare and examine evolutionary changes in genes across a number of species, including humans.

question_text: The details in paragraphs 12–14 about the platypus’s different abilities convey a central idea of the excerpt by
options: showing that the platypus has a gene that allows it to produce nutrient-rich milk, as humans do.
proving that the platypus, whose DNA is made up of DNA from several other species, has developed venom to defend itself.
suggesting that the platypus, while gaining traits in common with mammals and reptiles, has lost some bird-like traits.
demonstrating that the platypus has a rare evolutionary background that includes bird, reptile, and mammal DNA.

question_text: The author elaborates on the idea that creating a full analysis of platypus DNA was an important scientific endeavor mainly through
options: a description of the type of information about human genetics that specialized research can yield.
a comparison of the platypus with its closest bird and reptile relatives on the evolutionary tree.
the discussion of how unusual the platypus genome is in the animal kingdom.
the explanation of how genetics can be aligned to physiological function.

question_text: How can researching the genomes of other animals inform scientists’ understanding of human health and disease?
options: Tracking how other animals evolved over millions of years helps researchers preserve and sustain nature.
Finding ways that animal genomes are similar to the human genome helps researchers find signals that control genes.
Observing that all living things evolved from a common ancestor helps researchers pinpoint certain genetic traits.
Understanding how other animals are similar to one another helps researchers find new ways to understand the human genome.

question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt best supports the idea that the same DNA material results in the same traits even in different classes of animals?
options: “The findings cement what may have seemed totally obvious but turned out to be a bit of a scientific surprise: platypus DNA is a patchwork of genes from reptiles, birds, and mammals.” (paragraph 2)

“In other words, the platypus heritage is laid out in an evolutionary DNA tapestry that marks the time, hundreds of millions of years ago, when reptiles and mammals branched off the evolutionary tree.” (paragraph 3)
“The platypus is nothing like a human, so what can its DNA tell us about people and the diseases we get?” (paragraph 4)

“The evolutionary reason for maintaining such molecular weaponry isn’t yet clear, but what is fascinating is that it appears nature mixed and matched together DNA pieces separately to create the venom genes in reptiles and monotremes like the platypus.” (paragraph 14)

question_text: How does paragraph 1 introduce the idea that the Wright brothers knew that their flight attempt was risky?
options: through the mention of a signal to notify lifesaving experts that the flight attempt was about to begin
by providing specific details about the speed of the wind and the Wright brothers’ response to the windy conditions
by suggesting that a slower landing would be necessary at the end of the flight in order to maintain safety
through the indication that the Wright brothers waited indoors for most of the morning because of the poor weather

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 4.

Wilbur having used his turn in the unsuccessful attempt on the 14th, the right to thefirst trial now belonged to me.

The sentence contributes to the development of ideas in the excerpt by
options: demonstrating the challenge of the extreme winter conditions during the flight.
revealing how many tries it took for Wilbur Wright to finally get the machine to take flight.
demonstrating that both Orville and Wilbur Wright were eager to pilot what could potentially be the first flight.
suggesting a sense that both brothers felt confident they would soon succeed in completing the first flight.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 5.

This flight lasted only 12 seconds, but it was nevertheless the first in the history of the world in which a machine carrying a man had raised itself by its own power into the air in full flight, had sailed forward without reduction of speed and had finally landed at a point as high as that from which it started.

The words “only,” “nevertheless,” and “finally” most clearly convey the idea that
options: even a flight of such minor duration had taken a long time to achieve.
the short flight gave the Wright brothers hope for longer ones in the future.
the flight proved that the machine was, at last, capable of becoming airborne.
although it was brief, the flight was a remarkable accomplishment.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 5.

As the velocity of the wind was over 35 feet per second and the speed of the machine over the ground against this wind ten feet per second, the speed of the machine relative to the air was over 45 feet per second, and the length of the flight was equivalent to a flight of 540 feet made in calm air.

How does the sentence help convey Orville Wright’s perspective about this first flight?
options: It provides evidence that he maintained a scientific approach when attempting flight.
It emphasizes that he believed the flight was successful despite its short distance.
It provides a comparison between flight distances under calm and high wind conditions.
It highlights the importance of such calculations in the success of future flights.

question_text: How do the details in paragraph 5 about the uneven nature of the flight convey a central idea of the excerpt?
options: by explaining how the flawed design of the machine caused it to turn unpredictably in the air and brought the first flight by a person to an abrupt end
by indicating that the difficulty in controlling the flight was caused by the rudimentary instruments of the machine and the inexperience of the pilot
by explaining how the pilot and the plane overcame adverse conditions in order to complete the first piloted flight
by indicating that the gradual change in wind velocity created an extreme environment in which to maneuver the plane and maintain its flight

question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt best supports the idea that the Wright brothers had to adapt their flight plans to accommodate the weather conditions?
options: “When we arose on the morning of the 17th, the puddles of water, which had been standing about camp since the recent rains, were covered with ice.” (paragraph 1)
“We realized the difficulties of flying in so high a wind, but estimated that the added dangers in flight would be partly compensated for by the slower speed in landing.” (paragraph 1)
“After running the motor a few minutes to heat it up, I released the wire that held the machine to the track, and the machine started forward in the wind.” (paragraph 4)
“The course of the flight up and down was exceedingly erratic, partly due to the irregularity of the air, and partly to lack of experience in handling this machine.” (paragraph 5)

question_text: The use of chronological structure contributes to the development of ideas in the excerpt by
options: outlining the actions that the Wright brothers took to prepare for and successfully complete the first flight.
identifying the primary factors that allowed the Wright brothers to overcome obstacles and achieve the first flight.
showing how the Wright brothers applied lessons learned from their previous flight attempts to accomplish the first flight.
demonstrating how the Wright brothers analyzed the impact of wind velocity to identify the ideal conditions for the first flight.

question_text:
Read paragraph 2 from the excerpt.

To the proprietors of . . . mangy lynxes, moth-eaten coyotes, and dancing bears I returned courteous but uncompromising refusals—of course, first submitting all such letters, together with my replies, to Professor Farrago.

This paragraph helps develop the plot by establishing that the narrator
options: thinks that writing refusal letters for the animals offered to the zoological society is not necessary.
attempts to predict what the professor would say in the refusal letters.
believes that many of the animals offered are not acceptable for the zoological society.
resents the professor’s insistence on reviewing the refusal letters.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 3.

The professor, who was sitting at his desk before a pile of letters and replies submitted for approval by me, pushed his glasses down and looked over them at me with a whimsical smile that suggested amusement, impatience, annoyance, and perhaps a faint trace of apology.

What does the phrase “a faint trace of apology” convey about the professor?
options: It indicates that the professor feels bad that he has to call the narrator to his office after work.
It shows that the professor is hesitant to share his opinions with the narrator.
It implies that the professor is uncomfortable criticizing the narrator’s work.
It suggests that the professor knows that the conversation will be frustrating for the narrator.

question_text: How does the exchange between the professor and the narrator in paragraphs 8–11 contribute to the development of the excerpt?
options: It establishes the conflict between the professor and the narrator concerning the validity of the letter.
It suggests a theme of collaboration because the narrator and the professor regularly work together.
It reveals the characters’ traits by contrasting the narrator’s distrust of the content of the letter with how easily the professor is deceived by what he reads.
It hints that the resolution will involve the narrator accepting the professor’s opinion about the content of the letter.

question_text: The professor’s observations in paragraphs 15–17 create tension in the excerpt by causing the narrator to feel
options: flustered by the professor’s criticism of his logic.
annoyed by the professor’s sarcasm about his inexperience.
confused by the professor’s lack of respect for his opinion.
frustrated by the professor’s lack of interest in his theory.

question_text: How does the interaction between the narrator and the professor in paragraphs 26–28 contribute to the development of the theme?
options: It illustrates the professor’s patience as the narrator argues against making the expedition.
It reveals the narrator’s frustration with his limited role in making decisions for the zoological society.
It emphasizes the professor’s desire to acquire new specimens for the zoological society at any cost.
It shows the narrator’s acceptance of his assignment despite his personal objections.

question_text: How does the author develop the contrast between the narrator’s point of view and the professor’s point of view?
options: by providing both the narrator’s and professor’s thoughts on how age and experience influence each other’s reasoning
by using the conversation between the narrator and the professor to emphasize their reactions to the letter
by describing the professor’s persistent efforts to change the narrator’s mind about the letter
by including dialogue that explains why the professor is the supervisor and the narrator is his subordinate

question_text: How does paragraph 34 help develop the plot of the excerpt?
options: It shows that the narrator is beginning to consider the possibility of finding the great auks.
It demonstrates that the narrator is struggling to understand why the professor thinks the great auks exist.
It establishes that the narrator is willing to let the professor overrule him about the great auks.
It emphasizes that the narrator feels a sense of urgency to begin an expedition to locate the great auks.

question_text: Which sentence best demonstrates the professional relationship between the narrator and the professor?
options: “I said as much to Professor Farrago, but, to my surprise, he appeared to waver.” (paragraph 8)
“Clearly, Professor Farrago was on the verge of dotage—ah, what a loss to the world!” (paragraph 24)
“I drew a chair up beside his desk—there was nothing to do but to obey, and this fool’s errand was none of my conceiving.” (paragraph 25)
“ ‘Very well,’ said Professor Farrago, good-humoredly, ‘you shall have all the assistance you may require.’ ” (paragraph 29)

question_text: Which sentence from the excerpt best explains why the professor is eager to send the narrator on an expedition?
options: “ ‘Whatever it is that our correspondent has—and I am daring to believe that it is the great auk itself—I want you to secure it for the society.’ ” (paragraph 23)
“ ‘What I want you to do is to get those birds here safely.’ ” (paragraph 27)
“ ‘I suppose,’ he replied, with the same half-apologetic, half-humorous smile, ‘it is instinct.’ ” (paragraph 33)
“ ‘I can’t get away from the idea that we are on the eve of acquiring the rarest of living creatures.’ ” (paragraph 33)

question_text: What is the best summary of the discussion of congressional term policy outlined in paragraph 2?
options: While all members of Congress can be reelected an unlimited number of times, members of the House of Representatives and of the Senate serve different term lengths; this inequity has become troubling to many American citizens in recent years.

The discrepancy between the president having term limits and members of Congress having unlimited terms has come to seem like a governmental flaw to many American citizens, and this flaw could be remedied by imposing congressional term limits.

Support for congressional term limits is increasing, as shown by recent surveys indicating that American citizens of different backgrounds and political beliefs are beginning to favor implementation of term limits for members of Congress.

While the Constitution sets a term limit for the office of president, no such limit exists for members of Congress; however, recent surveys show that many American citizens are now in favor of term limits for members of Congress.

question_text: Which sentence from the passage supports the idea that congressional term limits would “benefit our government” (paragraph 2)?
options: “Currently, members of the House of Representatives, who serve two-year terms, and Senators, who serve six-year terms, can run for reelection an unlimited number of times.” (paragraph 2)

“Modern surveys conducted by multiple firms consistently show that American citizens of a variety of backgrounds and political leanings approve of the idea of setting term limits for members of Congress.” (paragraph 2)

“Former Senator Joe Lieberman, upon his retirement, suggested that Congress ‘might be healthier and less partisan and less rigid if it turned over more often, and term limits are one way to do that.’ ” (paragraph 3)

“Thomas E. Mann, Senior Fellow in governance studies at the Brookings Institution, notes that every decade, new members replace at least half the members of the House and the Senate, due to retirement or elections.” (paragraph 7)

question_text: The quotations in paragraph 3 convey a central idea of the passage by
options: emphasizing some of the possible effects term limits would have on how Congress functions.
showing that both politicians and law experts have strong opinions about congressional term limits.
suggesting that citizens defer to career politicians and law experts on issues such as congressional term limits.
implying that term limits would affect the ways that members of Congress campaign and vote.

question_text:
Read this sentence from paragraph 5.

While challenging the career politician’s path is seen as a benefit to term limit supporters, there is a possibility that a Congress mostly composed of newcomers could severely affect policy making.

Which statement best describes how the sentence fits into the overall structure of the passage?
options: It provides evidence for the idea that term limits are controversial.
It summarizes the consequences of having term limits.
It begins to explore the effects of instituting term limits
It shifts from the arguments for to the arguments against term limits.

question_text: According to paragraph 5, serving more terms improves politicians’ effectiveness by
options: motivating them to learn the congressional processes necessary to create legislation.
encouraging them to collaborate with politicians of the opposing party in order to pass legislation.
allowing them to gain expertise and develop strong political relationships.
enabling them to create new policies while fostering their own careers

question_text: According to the passage, why would setting term limits for members of Congress potentially increase the influence of special-interest groups?
options: Term limits would lead to a greater number of new representatives who rely on guidance and support from special-interest groups early in their terms.
Term limits would create a situation in which special-interest groups have to work more closely with the new representatives who replace experienced representatives.
Term limits would force experienced representatives out of their seats and bring in new representatives who focus on the agendas of special-interest groups.
Term limits would result in both new and experienced representatives looking to special-interest groups in order to influence decisions made in legislature.

question_text: The author of the passage develops the idea that congressional term limits might have negative effects mainly by
options: describing the amount of time it takes for new representatives to build connections with experienced representatives.
explaining why members of Congress need experience in order to govern well.
illustrating the various ways lobbyists seek to influence the decisions of new members of Congress.
revealing the statistics on the turnover rates for representatives.

question_text: With which statement would the author of the passage most likely agree?
options: The expertise of lawmakers should outweigh other considerations when it comes to deciding about term limits.
The decision to institute term limits for Congress is the most pressing issue facing American voters today.
There are compelling reasons both for and against setting term limits for Congress.
Special-interest groups are likely to have a huge influence on whether term limits are set.

question_text: The tables at the end of the passage contribute to the development of ideas in paragraph 7 by
options: highlighting the idea that the number of members of Congress who are reelected in each election has increased substantially since 1950.
demonstrating that the number of times members of Congress are reelected throughout their careers has shifted since 1950.
showing that the reelection rate in the Senate differs from the reelection rate in the House
emphasizing the fact that the Senate has fewer seats but a greater reelection rate than the House.

question_text: Ms. Li opened a retirement account with a deposit of $2,500. This account earns 4% simple interest annually. How many years will it take her to earn $500 on her $2,500 deposit?
